    "summary": "YES: Translator's Afterword — correct placement for critical context post-experience",
    "content": "YES — a Translator's Afterword.\n\nThis is the structurally correct placement for everything we've been struggling to fit into the Preface without spoilers. After the reader has experienced the essays, a Translator's Afterword can do what a Foreword or front-loaded structural claims cannot: discuss the work's significance with full specificity — the dissolution of absurdity, the nihilism-metaphysics relationship, the Poetic as a post-nihilistic stance, the cross-traditional connections (Heidegger's Gelassenheit, Camus's revolt, Nagarjuna's two truths, Wittgenstein's language games) — all without undermining a single experiential sequence. It also gives us a natural home for the kind of critical analysis the expert reports contain: why this work matters within existentialist thought, phenomenology, Chinese philosophy, etc. The reader arrives at the Afterword already equipped with the experiences; the Afterword helps them understand what they've been through."
  }
